t;.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;To =\r\ngive a simplisitc analogy, some jewllery may be gold mixed with some amount=\r\n of copper. If one jewllery is 100% pure gold, it does not mean it contains=\r\n all the gold in the\n world. It only means it has nothing other than gold. =\r\nSimilarly, the four poornavataras mentioned by Parasara are 100% divine and=\r\n do not contain jivamsa. It does not mean they contain &quot;all the divinity&quot; i=\r\nn cosmos.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;In fact, the very notion that =\r\nany one form can be &quot;the most complete or perfect avatara&quot; or &quot;one that per=\r\nsonifies entire divinity of Supreme Being&quot; or &quot;one equal to Supreme Being&quot; =\r\nis unacceptable and inconsistent with SB 1.3.30-31, which says that ANY for=\r\nm of Supreme Being is like a cloud in the sky, while Supreme Being is like =\r\nthe sky containing all possible clouds.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Supreme Being is endowed w=\r\nith infinite qualities. Any form contains a finite number of those qualitie=\r\ns. So no form can be &quot;equal to&quot; Supreme Being. SB 1.3.30-31 is clear in tha=\r\nt regard.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;If one form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being and others are\n =\r\nnot, you can conclude that that form is &quot;the best&quot;. If neither form is &quot;equ=\r\nal to&quot; supreme being, how can you really compare the different qualities of=\r\n two forms?\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Anyway, this renders your (3) =\r\na meaningless issue. Whether that line refers to Krishna alone or not is ir=\r\nrelevant, for, in either case, &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot; cannot mean &quot;a personifica=\r\ntion of the entirety of supreme being&quot;. Before you wonder whether it refers=\r\n to Krishna alone or not, first figure out what &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot; actually =\r\nmeans, in a way that is not inconsistent with verses that follow! If no for=\r\nm is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being and every form is a &quot;subset&quot; of supreme being=\r\n (like a cloud in sky), what is the meaning of &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot;???\n&gt;=C2=A0=\r\n\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Regarding (4), Parasara\n identified 4 avataras a=\r\ns 100% divine, with no jivamsa, and identified the source of divinity in ea=\r\nch of them. He only gave objective information and did not give any subject=\r\nive judgment on who is the best, which Suta apparently did.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;I have=\r\n not read BV Purana. If you can quote some verses before and after, I can c=\r\nomment. Any comparison between avataras WILL have to be under some subjecti=\r\nve context. I don&#39;t know the context of Suta&#39;s statement you allude to.\n&gt;=\r\n=C2=A0\n&gt;Though any comparison is subjective, I will be surprised if someone=\r\n considers the other two poornavataras of Vishnu as the &quot;best&quot; avataras. Bu=\r\nt, I will not be surprised if different people consider Rama and Krishna as=\r\n the most perfect avataras. Sun and Moon are the luminaries and show soul a=\r\nnd mind, which clearly have a primary significance compared to other aspect=\r\ns of consciousness! So Rama and Krishna are bound to be seen as the best by=\r\n different people. However, what Suta\n apparently said can only be a subjec=\r\ntive view under some context.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Regarding =\r\n(2): Kala means a part or a phase. Moon has 16 phases (representing 16 tith=\r\nis, including Amavasya and Pournima), but Sun has only one phase - he is al=\r\nways full and bright!\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Just like Moon, mind has many moods, even a =\r\nperfected one. A perfected mind goes through those moods with full awarenes=\r\ns of underlying reality, whereas an imperfect mind experiences them under d=\r\nelusion. But it is the nature of Moon/mind to have variations. Sun/soul OTO=\r\nH has no such variations.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Krishna may show Vishwaroopa oneday, run=\r\n away from battlefield another day (e.g. Jarasandha), do amazing miracles o=\r\nneday and play clever tricks another day. There is a lot more variety to hi=\r\ns personality than Rama&#39;s. Now, does that make him better or worse than Ram=\r\na? Well, that is\n a *subjective* matter.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;R=\r\negarding (1): Parasara said that paramatmamsa is present in several beings =\r\nsuch a planets, Brahma, Shiva, their consorts, etc. Grahas sustain the worl=\r\nd appearance in consciousness by grasping it based on karmaphala. So they s=\r\ntand for different qualities of Vishnu that sustain the world appearance. S=\r\no Vishnu&#39;s avataras are associated with grahas. But Pararsara said that ava=\r\ntaras can descend from the paramatmamsa present in several other beings (e.=\r\ng. Shiva, Parvati, Ashwins, Maruts etc). Unfortunately, we have meagre unde=\r\nrstanding what various deities stand for, what forces play a role in creati=\r\nng, sustaining and destroying the world appearance in consciousness. People=\r\n talk too much about Vedanta (end of Veda) and there is hardly any understa=\r\nnding of Veda. When it comes to Puranic stories, we think in terms of\n supe=\r\nrficial stories and not in terms of how it maps to what happens in consciou=\r\nsness.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Mohini was an avatara of Vishnu + Maheshwari. Nara & Naraya=\r\nna were incarnations of Narayana (i.e. Brahma + Vishnu + Shiva). I don&#39;t kn=\r\now about Dhanvantari and will pass for today. Dattatreya again was an incar=\r\nnation of Shiva + Vishnu + Brahma. Balarama is an incarnation of great serp=\r\nent Adi Sesha (like Lakshmana).\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;We need to go deeper into what the=\r\ny all stand for esoterically and what role they play in the functioning of =\r\nconsciousness, to understand this more. Hopefully another day..\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Adwaitins who are skeptical about notions taught by=\r\n Parasara (paramatmamsa, jivatmamsa, different sources of paramtmamsa etc) =\r\nshould realize one thing. Though all is Brahman, all did not come from Brah=\r\nman in one step. It all evolved in many steps\n and correspondingly there ar=\r\ne some steps in the process of liberation!\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;If a character in my dr=\r\neam tonight overcomes its conditioning in the dream, it will simply merge b=\r\nack into my mind and not into Brahman yet. Of course, it cannot do even tha=\r\nt until I actually will it. It is after all a character created and sustain=\r\ned in my mind!\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Same thing applies to us!\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Vedanta is not w=\r\nrong. But it is relevant and applicable at &quot;anta&quot;, i.e. the end. Most of us=\r\n may not yet be anywhere near &quot;the end&quot;.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;B=\r\nTW, I distinguished between Vishnu and \nNarayana above. If you study Naraya=\r\nna sooktam and Vishnu Sooktam, you \ncan understand the difference. In Vaish=\r\nnava traditions, they are \nconsidered one, but, strictly speaking, that is =\r\ninaccurate. Of course, \nyou can reach Narayana through Vishnu. But then, yo=\r\nu can reach Narayana \nthrough Rudra or Bhairava as well!\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt; I am afraid the world will keep getting more and more c=\r\nonvinced that\n&gt;&gt; this specific list