re is an u=\r\nnmistakeable connection of the form and sequence of these main avatars with=\r\n the evolution of life on earth. From the aquatic, to the amphibian, to the=\r\n land-animal, to the half-animal-half-man, to the dwarf man (first human li=\r\nfe form who immediately takes possession of this earth represented by Vaman=\r\na&#39;s 3 steps), to the Rajashik avatara of Parashurama moving around with an =\r\naxe, to the Sattwa Guna Avatara of Rama, to the Nirguna Avatara of Krshna. =\r\nAlso, this indicates that spirituality is not to be separated into another =\r\nworld, but is a progressive realization of the various manifestation and po=\r\ntentials that lie inherent in the consciousness and its development through=\r\n various life-forms. Larger spirituality of earth and evolution go hand in =\r\nhand. That is Nature&#39;s grand design for life on\n earth.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=\r\n&gt;4. In this specifc context, I am only focusing on the parable of these mai=\r\nn 9/10 Avatars. It is not my contention that if one worships say Matysa Ava=\r\ntara, one will not attain to a state of liberation of the soul. As is the n=\r\nature of spiritual cosmology in Hinduism, any Devata can lead a person to a=\r\nny depth of realization. And each one of the Avatars of Vishnu are self-rea=\r\nlized in their own way and can be consider super-massive spiritual dynamos.=\r\n\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A05. Of these, naturally, Rama and Krshna a=\r\nre most adored because they represent a stage of evolution, both inside as =\r\nwell as outside, which society can relate of much easier, in this age. Rama=\r\n represents, for me, the stage of most satwic mind. A satwic mind is in con=\r\ntrol of itself. It known how to transform the animal tendencies within and =\r\nwithout - monkeys - into a constructive force for a greater purpose. Howeve=\r\nr, as with a state of full Sattwa Guna, there can be instances, even though=\r\n few, of dejection. For it is static in nature and will change only when ci=\r\nrcumstances force it to. As per the Valmiki Ramayana, Rama did feel dejecte=\r\nd while searching for Sita in the forest. He did have a moments fear before=\r\n the final assault on Ravana, which was dispelled by Agsatha when the later=\r\n revealed the stotra of the Sun to Rama. At the end of the final battle, Ra=\r\nma tells Sita, in a most dispassionate manner, that he killed Ravana not to=\r\n rescue her, but it\n was the Dharma to do so, and to unhold his family hono=\r\nur. That too was the dharma of that age when he lived, family honor. The wa=\r\ny I look at this grand epic, and I bow humbly to the genius of Rishis Valmi=\r\nki for representing the things as they are, as a scribe, as a poet, as an o=\r\nbserver, and not adding his own preferences to it anywhere, in the 14 years=\r\n of tribulation that Rama faced which culminated into his killing Ravana, h=\r\ne changed into the most dispassionate leader, such that no personal conside=\r\nration or emotions or passions can overturn the Rajadharma. His life is a l=\r\nesson of what a true leader must be! Krshna, OTOH, had this immaculate deta=\r\nchment right from birth. I am not taking his=C2=A0 supernatural feats into =\r\naccount. It is his singular and constant detachment from situations, from p=\r\neople, from environment, from circumstances that mark his life. At the age =\r\nof eight, he decides to leave Vrindavana for Mathura. All his friends, his =\r\nfoster parents,\n his village-folks who so loved him, pleaded with him that =\r\nit would make no sense for him to leave the shelter, love and comfort of hi=\r\ns happy, settled village life and head into an unknown destiny and destinat=\r\nion. Krshna tried to reason with them, then he understood that they won&#39;t u=\r\nnderstand, he promised he will return back once his work in Mathura is over=\r\n. He never returned. Later, much later, when the Gopis came to him asking h=\r\nim to participate in their dance, he obliged. But the moment some of them s=\r\ntarted getting jealous and possessive of Krshna, he removed himself quietly=\r\n from the scene, saying that he belongs to everyone equally and no one has =\r\nany special right over him. When Shishupala abused Krshna, the later merely=\r\n kept dropping flowers on the floor, smiling and counting. The moment the 1=\r\n00th abuse was over, he swiftly cut off Shishupala&#39;s head and was back into=\r\n his poise. But when Bhurishrava unfairly accused Krshna of being a revolut=\r\nionist\n and charlatan, Krshna did not kill him. When Duryodhana, who used t=\r\no think of Krshna as another black magician, wanted to arrest him, Krshna s=\r\nhowed his vikarala roopa in the assembly of kings, yet he did not finish th=\r\ne enemies off. The very next moment he was back into his own poised self. N=\r\never in the whole Mahabharata is there one instance of his going overboard,=\r\n never a single shade of depression, equivocation, or lack of confidence in=\r\n his actions, irrespective of what others say or think of him. And then rig=\r\nht in the middle of the greatest war he had the perfect equipoise to delive=\r\nr the most sublime spiritual philosophy. That is why his life remains the b=\r\nest ideal of Karma-Yoga. For a true Karma-Yogi by definition can never be d=\r\nejected. It is impossible. Neither the action nor the results belong to the=\r\n instrument. When running away from the battle-field and killing Kaliya Yav=\r\nana, or when advising Bheema to tear apart Jarashanda, or gesturing Bheema\n=\r\n to hit Duryodhana below the waist, or getting Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Kr=\r\nshna, as if by some Divine Intuition, knew exactly how the situations must =\r\nbe lined up which would cause the destruction of these people. This kind of=\r\n knowledge cannot come by the rational thinking. But happens when one is co=\r\nnstantly and consciously connected to the Universal Force. We do not find t=\r\nhese kind of complex situations in the Rama Avatara, at least in the Valmik=\r\ni Ramayana. Of course, if we take the Adhbut Ramayana or such other auxilli=\r\nary texts and retelling, we get a different picture. In the Adbhuta Ramayan=\r\na we have a 1000 headed demon attacking Rama after he kills Ravana, and the=\r\nn Sita turns into Adya Shakti and demolishes the 1000 headed demon and Rama=\r\n worships her. But if we take only the Ramayana and the Mahabharata, the pi=\r\ncture that emerges is very clear. Rama is the embodiment of Sattwic mind. T=\r\nherefore he displays all the great characteristics of satwa, chief\n of whic=\r\nh is self-control, as well as the occasional sadness caused due to separati=\r\non from his wife Sita whom, at least until Ravana was destroyed, he loved v=\r\nery dearly. Satwa guna creates a true saint, but can also cause some grief =\r\nwhen the stability is shaken. Krshna was gunatita. He had no attachment to =\r\nanything in this world - man, women, deva, danava, friend, enemy - and ther=\r\nefore he was never affected any trace of negative emotion. His Ananda never=\r\n left him even in the most trying situations. 6. Buddha was great spiritual=\r\n force in this world. But I do not see him fit in the scheme of evolutionar=\r\ny Avatars. His realization, the one he advocated, is a static realization, =\r\nan end in a void. This is clearly denying of the reality of this earth. I f=\r\nind this not in tune with what either Rama or Krshna espoused. None of them=\r\n negated this world. If negation of this world and life is the final aim, t=\r\nhen why send so many avatars at crucial stages of\n evolutionary development=\r\n? If the spiritual impact on masses is the reason for Buddha being an Avata=\r\nra, then why not Jesus or Zorathrusta.? They are no less impactful in that =\r\nsense. But do they fit in the scheme of spiritual line that these 9 Avatara=\r\ns of Narayana indicate in a most logical manner? No. As such many vaishnava=\r\n traditions in parts of India, do not consider Buddha to be an avatara. Rea=\r\nlization, to be complete and holistic, must be both static and dynamic, out=\r\nside of life as well as inside of life. That is why the Tantras formed thei=\r\nr own kind of spiritual philosophy, of the world as body of Shakti and ther=\r\nefore an object of reverence and realization. 7. The original literature of=\r\n the Nath Yogis used to mention 9 chakras. These are centers of psychologic=\r\nal functions. 6 inside the human body and 3 too subtle, or non-developed in=\r\n most people, even seekers. It is my belief that each of the 9 Avataras - e=\r\nxcluding Buddha - correspond to the full\n power and force of one of these 9=\r\n Chakras. Similarly, the 9 grahas, or that which can modify consciousness o=\r\nr allow the consciousness to explore and express itself is various possibli=\r\nties, are 9 in number. The lagna is a reference point and not a graha. Ther=\r\nefore the chief Avatars who represent the parable of evolution are nine in =\r\nnumber. And the ninth of the sequence is yet to come. 8. I cannot comment o=\r\nn which graha would typically represent which Avatara. I know of what the B=\r\nPHS says, however, it is my belief - feel free to disagree with it -:)[one =\r\ncannot rule out some deep-rooted corruption of understanding or textual mis=\r\nrepresentation in this Kali-Yuga] - that the Atmah among the Avataras has n=\r\not yet appeared. It will be Kalki, or as Vimalananda seems to say in the Ag=\r\nhora books, Nishkalanka - the stainless one. There is only one thing which =\r\nis perfectly stainless, the Atmah .After a Nirguna/Gunatita awastha comes l=\r\niving in the full and complete\n purity and might and force and strength of =\r\nthe Atmah. By the sheer dint of his purity the last Avatara will burn away =\r\nopposing forces of this world and fulfill the purpose of evolution. Even Kr=\r\nshna used diplomacy at various points in his adult life to achieve his ends=\r\n. Kalki, I am speculating, won&#39;t even need that. The white horse and that s=\r\nword is a metaphor. He will be the only one capable enough to rectify the v=\r\narious errors and corruptions that beset our age. Well, this is how I look =\r\nat the story of Avataras. It is perfectly ok not to agree with my views, bu=\r\nt I am reasonably sanguine now that this is what is closer to truth. -Regar=\r\nds =C2=A0Rajarshi\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;awaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmab=\r\nuddhayah |param bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayamanuttamam ||[7:24]\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;From: Narasimha P.V.R. Rao &lt;pvr108@...&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;To: Vedic Wisdom &lt;=\r\nvedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; \n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Sent: Thursday, 25 April 2013 9:00 AM\n=\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Subject: [vedic-wisdom] Comparing Dasavataras!\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Namaste friends, =C2=A0 There was a discussion on Lord V=\r\nishnu&#39;s Dasavataras on a limited access forum on Facebook. A learned friend=\r\n wrote that &quot;Krshna is the God-man&quot;, &quot;Previous Avatars are a build-up to th=\r\nis stage&quot; and &quot;Buddha after Krshna is like going back from the linear progr=\r\nession of spirituality that the Avatars manifest one after the other upto K=\r\nrshna&quot;. =C2=A0 I want to emphatically disagree with this notion that Dasava=\r\ntars of a &quot;linear progression of spirituality..upto Krshna&quot;. =C2=A0 *=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 * =C2=A0 Each avatara represents an aspect of Supreme in a perfected=\r\n form. =C2=A0 Maharshi Parasara equated dasavataras with planets. Fo